		<td><b>Arcade-perfect &quot;Pac-Man&quot; version?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Is there a version of &quot;Pac-Man&quot;, for any console, that is actually arcade-perfect and plays exactly like the real board?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Sun Feb 02, 2014 3:13 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Arcade-perfect &quot;Pac-Man&quot; version?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I thought <em>Namco Museum</em> series had emulated <em>Pac-Man</em>, which would obviously play like <em>Pac-Man</em> because it uses the same ROMs. One problem with a console port is the use of a vertical monitor. <em>Pac-Man</em> has a visible display area 288 pixels tall, with the area between the north and south walls occupying 240 of those. You can't rely on more than about 208 lines being visible on NTSC. The emulated versions on newer consoles scale the graphics down to fit the whole screen within the NTSC safe area.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
