	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>rainwarrior</b> [ Mon Feb 03, 2014 8:34 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Arcade-perfect &quot;Pac-Man&quot; version?</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">DRW wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I thought <em>Namco Museum</em> series had emulated <em>Pac-Man</em>, which would obviously play like <em>Pac-Man</em> because it uses the same ROMs.</div><br />Do you know anything about the question if this game has any input lag? For example, here is a video that proves that &quot;Street Fighter II&quot; in &quot;Capcom Classics Collection&quot; has massive input lag, in comparison to the old PlayStation version or to MAME:<br /><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JoJzobmdGzU" class="postlink">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JoJzobmdGzU</a><br />Is it possible that this is the case with other emulated games as well?</div><br /><br />There shouldn't be an inherent input lag in emulators like MAME. There is no reason to buffer the input, at least not in any naive implementation. If the output is buffered by your television there could be lag inherent there, but that has nothing to do with the emulation. There is an inherent sound lag due to buffered audio vs. the immediate hardware output, but this is not usually a problem except with very specific types of games.<br /><br />Also, don't use triple buffering, only double buffering. Triple buffering can add 1 frame of lag (it's an option because it can increase performance at the cost of 1 frame of latency).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


